            <h3 style="
                        padding-top: 5pt;
                        padding-left: 11pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Notes:
            </h3>
            <p class="s18" style="
                        padding-left: 11pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                1<span class="s19">
                    Values given in Snellen decimal notation.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="s18" style="
                        padding-left: 11pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                2<span class="s19">
                    A value of at least 0.7 in one eye is recommended to
                    reduce the risk of undetected underlying eye
                    disease.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="s19" style="
                        padding-top: 1pt;
                        padding-left: 39pt;
                        text-indent: -27pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                <span class="s18">3</span> As defined in the
                <i>International Recommendations for Colour Vision
                    Requirements for Transport </i>by the Commission Internationale de l&#39;Eclairage
                (CIE-143-2001, including any subsequent versions).
            </p>
            <p class="s18" style="
                        padding-left: 11pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        line-height: 12pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                4<span class="s19">
                    Subject to assessment by a clinical vision specialist
                    where indicated by initial examination findings</span><span class="s21">.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="s18" style="
                        padding-left: 11pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                5<span class="s19">
                    Engine department personnel shall have a combined
                    eyesight vision of at least 0.4.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="s18" style="
                        padding-left: 11pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                6<span class="s19">
                    CIE colour vision standard 1 or 2.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="s18" style="
                        padding-top: 1pt;
                        padding-left: 11pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                7<span class="s19">
                    CIE colour vision standard 1, 2 or 3.</span>
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p class="s10" style="
                        padding-top: 4pt;
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                <a name="bookmark9">Visual correction</a>
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Medical practitioners should advise persons required to use
                spectacles or contact lenses to perform duties that they
                should have a spare pair or pairs, as required, conveniently
                available on board the ship.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <h3 style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Additional guidance
            </h3>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                If laser refractive surgery has been undertaken, recovery
                should be complete and the quality of visual performance,
                including contrast, glare sensitivity and the quality of
                night vision, should have been checked by a specialist in
                ophthalmology.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                All seafarers should achieve the minimum eyesight standard
                of 0.1 unaided in each eye (STCW Code, section B-I/9,
                paragraph 10). This standard may also be relevant to other
                seafarers to ensure visual capability under emergency
                conditions when visual correction may be lost or damaged.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Seafarers not covered by the STCW Convention&#39;s eyesight
                standards should have vision sufficient to perform their
                routine and emergency duties safely and effectively.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <h3 style="
                        padding-top: 4pt;
                        padding-left: 32pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: center;
                    ">
                Appendix B
            </h3>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <h3 style="
                        padding-top: 4pt;
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                <a name="bookmark10">Hearing standards</a>
            </h3>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p class="s10" style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Testing
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Hearing capacity for seafarers apart from those identified
                below should be an average of at least 30 dB (unaided) in
                the better ear and an average of 40 dB (unaided) in the less
                good ear within the frequencies 500, 1,000, 2,000 and 3,000
                Hz (approximately equivalent to speech-hearing distances of
                3 metres and 2 metres, respectively).
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                It is recommended that hearing examinations should be made
                by a pure tone audiometer. Alternative assessment methods
                using validated and standardized tests that measure
                impairment to speech recognition are also acceptable. Speech
                and whisper testing may be useful for rapid practical
                assessments. It is recommended that those undertaking
                deck/bridge duties are able to hear whispered speech at a
                distance of 3 metres.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Hearing aids are only acceptable in serving seafarers where
                it has been confirmed that the individual will be capable of
                safely and effectively performing the specific routine and
                emergency duties required of them on the vessel that they
                serve on throughout the period of their medical certificate.
                (This may well require access to a back-up hearing aid and
                sufficient batteries and other consumables.) Arrangements
                need to be in place to ensure that they will be reliably
                aroused from sleep in the event of an emergency alarm.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                If noise-induced hearing loss is being assessed as part of a
                health surveillance programme, different criteria and test
                methods will be required.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 24pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                It is recommended that national authorities indicate which
                tests for hearing are to be used, based on national
                audiological practices, using the above thresholds as
                criteria. Procedures should include the methods to be
                adopted in deciding if the use of a hearing aid is
                acceptable.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <h3 style="
                        padding-top: 4pt;
                        padding-left: 32pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: center;
                    ">
                <a name="bookmark11">Appendix C</a>
            </h3>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <h3 style="
                        padding-top: 4pt;
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                <a name="bookmark12">Physical capability requirements</a>
            </h3>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p class="s10" style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Introduction
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                The physical capability requirements for work at sea vary
                widely and have to take account of both routine and
                emergency duties. The functions that may require assessment
                include:
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                strength;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                stamina;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                flexibility;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                balance and coordination;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                size – compatible with entry into confined areas;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                exercise capacity – heart and respiratory reserve; and
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                fitness for specific tasks – wearing breathing apparatus.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p class="s10" style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Medical conditions and physical capability
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 70pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Limitations may arise from a range of conditions, such as:
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                high or low body mass/obesity;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                severely reduced muscle mass;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                musculoskeletal disease, pain or limitations to movement;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                a condition following an injury or surgery;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                lung disease;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                heart and blood vessel disease; and
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                some neurological diseases.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p class="s10" style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Physical capability assessment
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Physical capability testing should be undertaken when there
                is an indication for it, for instance because of the
                presence of one of the above conditions or because of other
                concerns about a seafarer&#39;s physical capabilities. The
                aspects that are tested will depend on the reasons for doing
                it. Table B-I/9 gives recommendations for physical
                capability abilities to be assessed for those seafarers
                covered by the STCW Convention, 1978, as amended, based on
                the tasks undertaken at sea.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-top: 4pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: right;
                    ">
                The following approaches may be used to assess whether the
                requirements in table B-I/9 are met:
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Observed ability to do routine and emergency duties in a
                safe and effective way.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Tasks that simulate normal and emergency duties.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 21pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: right;
                    ">
                Assessment of cardio-respiratory reserve, including
                spirometry and ergometric tests.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                This will predict maximum exercise capacity and hence the
                seafarer&#39;s ability to perform physically demanding work.
                A large reserve will also indicate that heart and lung
                performance is less likely to be compromised in the next few
                years. The benchmark test is maximum oxygen uptake (VO2
                max). This requires dedicated equipment. Step tests such as
                the Chester or the Harvard, are simpler alternatives, which
                may be used for screening. If step tests are abnormal, they
                should be further validated (e.g. VO2 max or treadmill
                stress tests).
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Informal testing of reserve, for instance climbing three to
                six flights of stairs and assessing any distress, plus the
                speed of pulse rate decline on stopping. This is not readily
                reproducible but can be used for repeat assessment at the
                same location by the same medical practitioner.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Clinical assessment of strength, mobility, coordination,
                etc.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Additional information may come from activities recently or
                regularly undertaken, as described by the seafarer, such as:
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                physically demanding duties on the vessel, e.g. carrying
                weights or handling mooring equipment;
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        line-height: 13pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                attendance at a physically demanding course within the last
                two years,
            </p>
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        line-height: 13pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                e.g. fire-fighting, helicopter escape or STCW basic
                training; and
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="-">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 91pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                a confirmed personal pattern of regular strenuous exercise.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p class="s10" style="padding-left: 27pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: justify">
        Interpretation of results
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <ol id="l17">
        <li data-list-text="1">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Is there any evidence that the seafarer is not able to
                perform their routine and emergency duties effectively?
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="2">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 70pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Are there any observed limitations to strength, flexibility,
                stamina or coordination?
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="3">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 70pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                What is the outcome of any test for cardio-respiratory
                reserve?
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <ol id="l18">
                <li data-list-text=".1">
                    <p style="
                                padding-left: 112pt;
                                text-indent: -42pt;
                                text-align: justify;
                            ">
                        Test performance limited by shortness of breath,
                        musculoskeletal or other pain, or exhaustion. Causes
                        need to be investigated and taken into account in
                        determining fitness.
                    </p>
                    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text=".2">
                    <p style="
                                padding-left: 112pt;
                                text-indent: -42pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Unable to complete test.
                    </p>
                    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text=".3">
                    <p style="
                                padding-left: 112pt;
                                text-indent: -42pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Completed but stressed or with poor recovery after
                        stopping.
                    </p>
                    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text=".4">
                    <p style="
                                padding-left: 112pt;
                                text-indent: -42pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Completed to good or average standard.
                    </p>
                    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="4">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 27pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Discuss subjective feelings during the test with the subject
                and also go over experiences of fitness and capability when
                doing normal tasks and emergency drills. Obtain
                corroboration from others if performance at work uncertain.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p class="s10" style="
                padding-top: 4pt;
                padding-left: 27pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                text-align: left;
            ">
        Decision-making
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 27pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
        Information from a range of sources may be required and many of
        these are not easily accessed in the course of a medical
        examination:
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <ol id="l19">
        <li data-list-text="1">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 70pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Is there any indication that physical capability may be
                limited (e.g. stiffness, obesity or history of heart
                disease)?
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <ol id="l20">
                <li data-list-text=".1">
                    <p style="
                                padding-left: 112pt;
                                text-indent: -42pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        No – do not test.
                    </p>
                    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text=".2">
                    <p style="
                                padding-left: 112pt;
                                text-indent: -42pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Yes – consider what tests or observations will
                        enable the seafarer&#39;s capability to perform
                        their routine and emergency duties to be determined.
                        Go to (2).
                    </p>
                    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text="2">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 70pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Do the test results indicate that capabilities may be
                limited?
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <ol id="l21">
        <li data-list-text=".1">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 112pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                No – provided there are no underlying conditions that affect
                conduct of assessment. Able to perform all duties worldwide
                within designated department.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text=".2">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 112pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Yes – but duties can be modified to enable safe working,
                without putting excess responsibilities on others. Able to
                perform some but not all duties (R).
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text=".3">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 112pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Yes – but cause of limitation can be remedied. Incompatible
                with reliable performance of essential duties safely or
                effectively (T).
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        </li>
        <li data-list-text=".4">
            <p style="
                        padding-left: 112pt;
                        text-indent: -42pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Yes – but cause of limitation cannot be remedied.
                Incompatible with reliable performance of essential duties
                safely or effectively (P).
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <h3 style="padding-left: 98pt; text-indent: -70pt; text-align: left">
