                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 69pt;
                                text-indent: -28pt;
                                text-align: justify;
                            ">
                        Recurrence rates: Where the terms very low, low and
                        moderate are used for the excess likelihood of a
                        recurrence. These are essentially clinical
                        judgements but, for some conditions, quantitative
                        evidence on the likelihood of recurrence is
                        available. Where this is available, e.g. for seizure
                        and cardiac events, it may indicate the need for
                        additional investigations to determine an
                        individual&#39;s excess likelihood of a recurrence.
                    </p>
                    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 40pt;
                                text-indent: 0pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Quantitative recurrence levels approximate to:
                    </p>
                    <ul id="l66">
                        <li data-list-text="-">
                            <p class="s20" style="
                                        padding-left: 91pt;
                                        text-indent: -22pt;
                                        text-align: left;
                                    ">
                                Very low: recurrence rate less than 2 per
                                cent per year;
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li data-list-text="-">
                            <p class="s20" style="
                                        padding-left: 91pt;
                                        text-indent: -22pt;
                                        text-align: left;
                                    ">
                                Low: recurrence rate 2-5 per cent per year;
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li data-list-text="-">
                            <p class="s20" style="
                                        padding-left: 91pt;
                                        text-indent: -22pt;
                                        text-align: left;
                                    ">
                                Moderate: recurrence rate 5-20 per cent per
                                year.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p class="s20" style="
                        padding-left: 69pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                ** Asthma severity definitions:
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p class="s27" style="
                        padding-left: 40pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        line-height: 11pt;
                        text-align: left;
                    ">
                Childhood asthma:
            </p>
            <ul id="l67">
                <li data-list-text="-">
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 90pt;
                                text-indent: -21pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Mild: Onset age &gt;ten, few or no hospitalizations,
                        normal activities between episodes, controlled by
                        inhaler therapy alone, remission by age 16, normal
                        lung function.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text="-">
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 90pt;
                                text-indent: -21pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Moderate: Few hospitalizations, frequent use of
                        reliever inhaler between episodes, interference with
                        normal exercise activity, remission by age 16,
                        normal lung function.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text="-">
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 90pt;
                                text-indent: -21pt;
                                text-align: left;
                            ">
                        Severe: Frequent episodes requiring treatment to be
                        made more intensive, regular hospitalization,
                        frequent oral or IV steroid use, lost schooling,
                        abnormal lung function.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p class="s27" style="
                        padding-left: 40pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        line-height: 11pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Adult asthma:
            </p>
            <p class="s20" style="
                        padding-left: 69pt;
                        text-indent: 0pt;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                Asthma may persist from childhood or start over the age of
                16. There is a wide range of intrinsic and external causes
                for asthma developing in adult life. In late-entry recruits
                with a history of adult onset asthma, the role of specific
                allergens, including those causing occupational asthma,
                should be investigated. Less specific inducers such as cold,
                exercise and respiratory infection also need to be
                considered. All can affect fitness for work at sea.
            </p>
            <ul id="l68">
                <li data-list-text="-">
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 90pt;
                                text-indent: -21pt;
                                text-align: justify;
                            ">
                        Mild intermittent asthma: Infrequent episodes of
                        mild wheezing occurring less than once every two
                        weeks, readily and rapidly relieved by beta agonist
                        inhaler.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text="-">
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 90pt;
                                text-indent: -21pt;
                                text-align: justify;
                            ">
                        Mild asthma: Frequent episodes of wheezing requiring
                        use of beta agonist inhaler or the introduction of a
                        corticosteroid inhaler. Taking regular inhaled
                        steroids (or steroid/long-acting beta agonists) may
                        effectively eliminate symptoms and the need for use
                        of beta agonist treatment.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text="-">
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 90pt;
                                text-indent: -21pt;
                                text-align: justify;
                            ">
                        Exercise-induced asthma: Episodes of wheezing and
                        breathlessness provoked by exertion, especially in
                        the cold. Episodes may be effectively treated by
                        inhaled steroids (or steroid/long-acting beta
                        agonist) or other oral medication.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li data-list-text="-">
                    <p class="s20" style="
                                padding-left: 90pt;
                                text-indent: -21pt;
                                text-align: justify;
                            ">
                        Moderate asthma: Frequent episodes of wheezing
                        despite regular use of inhaled steroid (or
                        steroid/long acting beta agonist) treatment
                        requiring continued use of frequent beta agonist
                        inhaler treatment, or the addition of other
                        medication, occasional requirement for oral
                        steroids.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p class="s28" style="
                        padding-left: 90pt;
                        text-indent: -21pt;
                        line-height: 93%;
                        text-align: justify;
                    ">
                -
                <span class="s20">Severe asthma: Frequent episodes of wheezing and
                    breathlessness, frequent hospitalization, frequent use
                    of oral steroid treatment.</span>
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
